What is the structure of your dataset?

The following information taken directly from https://s3.amazonaws.com/udacity-hosted-downloads/ud651/wineQualityInfo.txt

Description of Input Variables

1 - fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)

2 - volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste

3 - citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines

4 - residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, it’s rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet

5 - chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine

6 - free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine

7 - total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine

8 - density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content

9 - pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale

10 - sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant

11 - alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine

Output variable (based on sensory data):

12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

An interesting note is that the authors point out that they are unsure whether all the input variable are relevant. If too many variables with a high correlation are left in this could harm the regression.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Main feature of interest is the quality scores as this is the output variable. The main point of this exploration is to find out which input variables are useful predictors of quality.This is of course subject to the major caveat that Quality itself is not an objective measure, and furthermore that the quality of this non- objective measure (a wine experts ability to consistently and accurately grade wine in a controlled blind environment) has been called into question (read: completely debunked) by numerous recent studies.

www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/jun/23/wine-tasting-junk-science-analysis

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
###investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I think that the outliers will provide a useful insight into the grades received. I would expect that the wines with a massive concentration of salt / acid would tend towards lower scores.

No - I felt that whilst this woud be possible ( IE create bound S02 measure by subtracting free SO2 from total S02), I felt that this was unlikely to provide any extra insight. After all, the curators have not included it in the dataset - I am assuming they know more about wine than me.

Reflection

Overall I would say that despite the lack of a continuous output variable and my overall unfamiliarity with wine I was able to explore several interesting aspects of the data, in particular testing what appear to be inaccurate assumptions about how several variables would relate to quality based on the descriptions provided.

The major hurdle in this project was grappling with the inherent biases of the distributions and finding a clear way of accounting for this.

My background reading on the topic revealed that wine is an incredibly complex product, so there are many many more chemical variables to explore. Moreover as mentioned previously, the output metric - quality is very questionable given the evidence against the ability of wine tasters to consistently grade wines. However it should be noted that the quality metric used in this dataset is itself a median, and the gradings are rather broad, so this would offset any inaccuracy and still provide a good general sense of whether a wine is good or not.
